History of Facebook
David Fincher's new film is, first of all, a story about paradox.
The film tells the story of the invention of Facebook, one of the pioneering tools in the field of the Internet, which united the whole world, quarreled five friends and made its creator - 26-year-old former Harvard student Mark Zuckerberg - the youngest billionaire of recent decades.
Jesse Eisenberg in the title role is just as brilliant as our conflicted genius, an emotionally isolated social exile with an unpredictable set of motivations and attachments.
Zuckerberg is launching the site for a variety of reasons: partly out of anger at the world around him, partly out of sporting interest, and partly just because IT is "cool."
The idea itself and its implementation may seem spontaneous and spontaneous, but the actual course of events hints at a clear calculation and a well-thought-out business plan.
The strengths of The Social Network become evident from the first frames, especially in the scene before the opening credits, where Zuckerberg is talking in a bar with his ex-girlfriend Erika (Mara): the sonorous, tough dialogues of screenwriter Aaron Sorkin gain strength here and do not soften until the very end.
The same goes for Fincher's direction: relatively restrained (with the exception of the Winklevoss twins, the actors were different from each other.
The face of one of them was superimposed on the other with the help of computer graphics.
At the same time as Zuckerberg, Natalie Portman studied at Harvard.
Rooney Mara got the lead role in Fincher's next film, The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo.
DIRECTOR: David Fincher
CAST: Jesse Eisenberg, Andrew Garfield, Rooney Mara, Justin Timberlake, Ermy Hammer, Joshua Pence
SYNOPSIS: Gloomy and introverted Harvard student Mark Zuckerberg, having received a turn from the gate on the personal front, takes on the ambitious task of creating a fundamentally new social network.
As Facebook's popularity grows, relationships with a few companion friends begin to fall apart and eventually lead to lawsuits.
The color palette plays its role: warm, sometimes sunny, even in the dark remaining cozy, it maneuvers between two tangled chains of events and two separate litigations.
Outside of the flow of incessant discussions, there is not much going on in the film: not a single death, not a single murder, and all of Zuckerberg's legal troubles are unlikely to be worth at least an additional paragraph for his meager Wikipedia page.
What attracted 49-year-old Sorkin and 48-year-old Fincher in this not too generous story?
After watching, there is a strong feeling that "The Social Network" is a portrait of our time, and understatement in this case is an important artistic device.
Only twenty years ago, Wall Street was doing much the same thing, only on a larger scale, with cosmic egos and big things.
Now that daily solvency has become even higher, politics is no longer carried out at board meetings, but in sandboxes.
Zuckerberg wants to be special, dreams of becoming the center of attention.
Severin (Garfield) is hurt that his best friend has a new best friend (Timberlake) and now he has no one to play with.
