At the beginning of the XVII century, when Ivan Susanin lived, surnames of people of humble origin had not yet really begun to appear.
They made do with the name "so-and-so, so-and-so son".
That is, patronyms were in use - nicknames from the father.
But sometimes, for example, in the case of remarriages of the father, a matronym was used - a nickname after the mother's name.
Susanin is just such a case: "Ivan, son of Susanna".
The serfs of small landowners really did without surnames for a long time - why do you need it, when you have 20 souls and everything is constantly in sight.
But the owners of estates of many thousands were forced to give their peasants surnames.
Thus, the serfs of Prince Andrei Cherkassky already at the beginning of the XVIII century had surnames without exception.
In the XIX century, even small landowners did not keep a peasant on the land, but let him go on rent - let him earn money by craft and pay the owner.
Such a peasant was entitled to a passport, where the surname had to be entered.
By the abolition of serfdom in Central Russia, 55% of the serfs were released for rent.
This means that they already had surnames.
