A powerful explosion was heard tens of kilometers away, but there were no casualties.
Norfolk County Police announced that, although the explosion was unplanned, none of the military personnel involved in defusing the bomb were injured.
"The device detonated shortly after work began on its neutralization.
Fortunately, all the personnel are intact.
Departments have begun to assess the damage," Norfolk Assistant Chief of Police Nick Davison told reporters.
Local residents write on social networks that the explosion shook houses at a distance of 24 km.
Photo by: Sky Revolutions
Photo caption: The explosion happened contrary to the plans of the sappers, but there were no killed or wounded
A 250-kilogram bomb was found during construction work on the banks of the Yar River, at the mouth of which, on the North Sea, stands Great Yarmouth.
Before starting attempts to defuse the bomb, the sappers built a protective rampart of sand around it, and the cordon, inside which outsiders were not allowed, was set up at a distance of 200 meters.
At first, on Thursday, bomb technicians were going to cut off the fuse from the bomb with the help of a robot, but the attempt failed, and then they decided, according to the local press, to use the technique of "slow burning" of explosives.
In the process of this burning, the explosion occurred.
During World War II, the Nazis dropped hundreds of thousands of bombs on Britain.
In the eight-month intensive bombing campaign from the autumn of 1940 to the spring of 1941, known as "Blitz", 450,000 bombs were dropped on Britain.
Among Belarusian researchers, women make up almost 40%
In Belarus, the number of women among researchers is 38.9%, BelTA learned from Alesya Solovey, a researcher at the Institute of Sociology of the National Academy of Sciences.
The proportion of women among candidates of sciences and doctors of sciences is also growing: among candidates of sciences women account for 41.1%, among doctors of sciences - 21%.
In all fields of science, with the exception of technical sciences, the proportion of women exceeded 50 per cent.
The most feminized area of scientific knowledge is the medical sciences, in which the proportion of women is 64.4 per cent.
Only in technical sciences do men predominate, women make up 26.7%.
In the National Academy of Sciences, the share of women among researchers is 49.1%, which is 10.2% more than in the country as a whole.
Among candidates of sciences, the proportion of women is 46%, among doctors of sciences - 20%.
More than half of the teaching staff in higher education institutions are women (57%).
Among the vice-rectors for scientific, educational and educational work, every third is a woman (31.8%), among deans - 38.7%, deputy deans - 44.6%, heads of departments - 42.5%.
Most women are among senior teachers and teachers - over 60%.
The proportion of women among associate professors in departments is also high (55.2%).
According to the republican monitoring of public opinion conducted by the Institute of Sociology of the National Academy of Sciences last year, the majority of Belarusians do not support gender stereotypes about women's opportunities in science.
63.5% (56.5% of men and 69% of women) disagree with the gender stereotype "science is a man's field of activity" to one degree or another.
More than half of the country's residents do not hold the opinion that a woman is less competent as a scientist - 66.1% (59% of men and 71.6% of women).
"The transformation of gender ideas about women's research competence in the mass consciousness contributes to the involvement of young women in science, the development of their creative potential, the formation of a successful role model of a woman scientist, including through the transfer of experience and the institution of mentoring," said Alesya Solovey.
On February 11, the International Day of Women and Girls in Science is celebrated annually.
The holiday was established to introduce women and girls to the field of science, encourage women to develop scientific careers and recognize the achievements of women in science.
According to UNESCO, women make up 30% of the total number of researchers in the world.
The likelihood of a further increase in the key rate is higher than its reduction
This statement was made by Bank of Russia Governor Elvira Nabiullina following a meeting of its Board of Directors on February 10, which decided to keep this rate at 7.50%.
The head of the regulator, in particular, noted that important changes have recently taken place.
On the one hand, the terms of foreign trade have noticeably worsened - the price of Russian oil has decreased.
On the other hand, the situation in the economy is developing better than the October forecast.
The shift in the structure of demand continues: consumption remains restrained, private investment slows down, but fiscal spending grows.
At the same time, pro-inflationary risks have generally increased.
"Therefore, this year the probability of raising the rate exceeds the probability of reducing it.
The expediency of changing the rate will be determined by the development of the situation," Nabiullina said.
In addition to the more pronounced impact of fiscal policy, she noted three risks.
First, a rapid unwinding of consumption in the face of elevated inflation expectations, if the factors that restrain consumer activity weaken.
Secondly, there is an increasing shortage of labor and a lag in the growth of labor productivity from the growth of wages.
And there are still risks of additional tightening of sanctions restrictions.
Speaking about the regulator's future decisions, the Governor of the Bank of Russia noted that, despite the previously noted strengthening of pro-inflationary factors, the inflation forecast for the current year remains at the level of 5-7%.
According to her, this may require a higher trajectory of the key rate than expected in October.
In the updated forecast of the Central Bank for this and next year, the ranges for the average key rate have been increased by half a percentage point, to 7.0-9.0% per annum for 2023 and 6.5-7.5% per annum for 2024.
"This does not exclude the possibility of a rate cut this year, but its probability and scale have decreased.
And on the contrary, the likelihood has increased that some rate hike may be needed in order for inflation to meet the target of close to 4% in 2024," the head of the Bank of Russia concluded.
The Bank of Russia has approved the requirements for the procedure for creating special closed-end mutual investment funds (UIFs) consisting of blocked foreign securities.
The regulator informs that such securities will be withdrawn from existing retail mutual funds.
This will make it possible to launch the management of the remaining liquid assets and resume operations with investment shares.
If a retail mutual fund contains more than 10% of blocked securities, then the management company must allocate them to a separate closed-end mutual fund by September 1, 2023.
Each shareholder will be given units of the new fund in an amount equal to the shares of the fixed fund.
It is also possible to change the status of the retail fund to a closed one.
For funds with a share of blocked securities of less than 10%, the new requirements are not mandatory.
But the management company has the right to allocate the blocked assets to a separate closed-end mutual fund.
In addition, a requirement is introduced to inform shareholders about the consequences of withdrawing blocked securities to a special mutual fund.
In the future, in the event of the sale of such securities, management companies are required to pay at least 90% of the proceeds to the owners of investment shares on a quarterly basis, the Bank of Russia said in a statement.
