How pregnant Russian women got stuck in Argentina
The Argentine Migration Service has begun to suspend and cancel the residence permits of Russians who received it through the birth of a child, but did not stay in the country.
Earlier, the authorities of the republic denied entry into the country to several pregnant Russian women, who were suspected of arriving for the purpose of "maternity tourism".
On February 11, they were nevertheless allowed to enter Argentina by a court decision.
More details - in the material "Gazeta. Ru".
The Argentine Migration Service has begun to suspend and cancel the residence permit (residence permit) of Russians who received it through the birth of a child, but did not stay in the country.
This was told to the C5N TV channel by the director of the service, Florencia Carignano.
"What we are doing is suspending the residence permits of those Russians who came to obtain a residence permit because their child is Argentine, but at the same time spent more time outside (Argentina) than inside (the country)," she explained.
According to her, when the court considers the issue of Argentine citizenship for a Russian, the migration service will submit data that the residence permit was suspended because this person "spent a month in Argentina and never came again."
Carignano warned that Russians who received a residence permit after the birth of a child and left may have it revoked.
Against this background, on February 9, it became known that three pregnant Russian women were "stuck" at the airport in Argentina due to the refusal to enter the country.
According to the head of the consular department of the Russian Embassy in Argentina, Georgy Polin, the diplomatic mission connects the incident with the fact that the authorities of the republic could consider the information provided by the girls at the entrance to be incomplete or false.
One of them arrived on February 7, two more on the evening of February 8, RIA Novosti reports.
The diplomat stressed that more pregnant women flew to Argentina, but these three were issued an order not to be allowed into the country.
"They were not allowed into the country in accordance with the law on migration, where one of the grounds for not being allowed into the country is the provision of incomplete, false, distorted information," Polin said.
On Saturday, February 11, the Argentine migration service, by court decision, allowed pregnant citizens of the Russian Federation to enter the country, lawyer Christian Rubilar said.
"An hour ago, they were all allowed to enter Argentina," TASS quoted him as saying.
Rubilar noted that the migration service changed its decision after the court ruling.
It is easier for foreign parents of a child born in Argentina to obtain a passport of the republic.
It allows short-term trips to 171 countries without visas, including the EU states, the UK and Japan, RBC notes.
In early January 2023, The Guardian newspaper wrote about the "boom in maternity tourism" to Argentina among Russians.
According to Polin, in 2022, from 2 thousand to 2.5 thousand citizens of the Russian Federation moved to the republic.
Many of them, the diplomat noted, are Russian women who are going to give birth there.
"In 2023, this number could grow to 10 thousand," he said.
In turn, Carignano previously claimed that in 2022 about 10.5 thousand Russian citizens arrived in Argentina, and in recent months - more than 5.8 thousand pregnant women.
