Depressurization of Progress MS-21 occurred on the ISS: 12 February 2023, 00:12
TASS - KAZINFORM - Roscosmos reported on the depressurization of Progress MS-21, prepared for undocking from the ISS, Kazinform reports with reference to TASS.
"The contour of the Progress MS-21 transport cargo ship, the flooding of which is scheduled for February 18, is depressurized, confirmed the telemetry data received by the MCC," the press service of Roscosmos said.
As noted, at the moment it is isolated from the total volume of the station.
The causes of the incident are being investigated, it did not affect either the docking of the Progress MS-22 cargo spacecraft or the further ISS flight program.
The situation was commented on by Roscosmos Executive Director for Manned Space Programs Sergei Krikalev.
"On the cargo ship, which has been docked to the station for several months, there was a leak of coolant from the thermal control system.
The situation is somewhat similar to what happened to us with the spacecraft (Soyuz MS-22 - approx. TASS) in mid-December," he said, noting that the commission that analyzed the incident with the Soyuz concluded that the leak was caused by a micrometeoroid.
Roscosmos will conduct an analysis to make sure there are no problems with the next launches.
"We need to conduct an in-depth analysis to make sure that this reason does not apply to similar designs in future launches.
This is the most important task that will now face us," he said.
According to the executive director, it is necessary to conduct an analysis in terms of preparing the spacecraft for launch, the materials that were used, and the technologies that were used in the assembly of the radiator.
The same analysis was carried out in the case of the damaged radiator of the Soyuz MS-22 spacecraft.
"The most important thing is to make sure that this is not some kind of systematic error," Krikalev added.
The executive director clarified that on Saturday, a commission began its work, which will analyze all possible causes.
"The spacecraft was supposed to undock and descend from orbit two days before the launch of the Soyuz spacecraft (Soyuz MS-23 - approx. TASS), so there are serious consequences for the actions of the crew, for the work of the crew... From this point of view, this will not affect the program," Krikalev said.
The Progress MS-21 truck was launched from Baikonur on a Soyuz-2.1a launch vehicle on October 26.
Two days later, it docked with the Poisk small research module of the Russian segment of the ISS.
The spacecraft delivered more than 2,500 kg of cargo to the ISS.
